1
00:00:13,491 --> 00:00:15,450
[BICYCLE BELL JINGLING]

2
00:00:15,580 --> 00:00:17,365
[DOG BARKING]

3
00:00:17,495 --> 00:00:19,541
[DOG WHIMPERING]

4
00:00:28,550 --> 00:00:30,726
[PLAYING PIANO]

5
00:00:36,297 --> 00:00:38,168
[LOUD MUSIC BLARING]

6
00:00:38,299 --> 00:00:39,952
Excuse me!

7
00:00:42,781 --> 00:00:46,437
Could you please turn
 your so-called music down?

8
00:00:49,223 --> 00:00:50,485
Hello?

9
00:00:50,615 --> 00:00:52,139
<i>♪</i>

10
00:00:54,619 --> 00:00:56,839
<i>♪ I'm all right</i>

11
00:00:56,969 --> 00:00:58,580
<i>♪ I'm all right</i>

12
00:01:01,496 --> 00:01:02,671
<i>♪ I'm all right </i>

13
00:01:03,193 --> 00:01:04,368
Hello?

14
00:01:08,329 --> 00:01:09,591
Grandmother, please!

15
00:01:10,592 --> 00:01:12,985
-It's too loud!
 -[MUSIC TURNS OFF]

16
00:01:13,116 --> 00:01:15,249
It's rock 'n' roll,
 sweetheart.

17
00:01:15,379 --> 00:01:16,424
-It's never too loud.
 -[LOUD MUSIC PLAYING]

18
00:01:17,120 --> 00:01:18,774
I can't hear myself think.

19
00:01:18,904 --> 00:01:21,124
That's exactly why
 it was invented.

20
00:01:23,387 --> 00:01:25,433
-[MUSIC TURNS OFF]
 -Don't you think
 you're overdoing it?

21
00:01:25,563 --> 00:01:28,305
Honey, at my age,
 being able to overdo

22
00:01:28,436 --> 00:01:30,264
is more important than
 being able to do.

23
00:01:30,394 --> 00:01:31,395
[PANTING]

24
00:01:31,526 --> 00:01:33,658
You're not exactly, Jurassic.

25
00:01:33,789 --> 00:01:35,138
Thank you, sweetheart.

26
00:01:35,269 --> 00:01:38,576
Like or not,
things change.

27
00:01:38,707 --> 00:01:40,578
They still want to
 close the school?

28
00:01:40,709 --> 00:01:43,494
Enrollment's down,
 repair bill's up.

29
00:01:43,625 --> 00:01:46,149
We either raise
 enough money to meet
 the state matching funds

30
00:01:46,280 --> 00:01:47,542
or it's all over.

31
00:01:49,065 --> 00:01:50,936
As soon as
 something gets old,

32
00:01:51,067 --> 00:01:52,982
nobody sees
 the beauty in it anymore.

33
00:01:53,983 --> 00:01:55,289
I'm depressing myself.

34
00:01:56,899 --> 00:01:59,815
Is this about saving
 the school or preventing
 Sue Ellen Caldwell

35
00:01:59,945 --> 00:02:01,643
from developing the property?

36
00:02:01,773 --> 00:02:05,299
Just because that woman
 has been trying
 to get the best of me

37
00:02:05,429 --> 00:02:08,215
since I was your age,
 does not mean that...

38
00:02:10,304 --> 00:02:12,697
There is a principle
 behind this.

39
00:02:12,828 --> 00:02:16,614
She is a mean, selfish,
 rich, bully-snob,

40
00:02:16,745 --> 00:02:18,703
and I'm gonna get her
 if it's the last thing I do.

41
00:02:19,530 --> 00:02:20,749
At least it's not personal.

42
00:02:20,879 --> 00:02:22,098
Don't you have school?

43
00:02:22,229 --> 00:02:23,404
You're the one
 who's gonna be late.

44
00:02:23,534 --> 00:02:25,928
Dad's back from DC.
 He's dropping me off.

45
00:02:26,058 --> 00:02:27,886
-Now change!
 -[SCOFFS]

46
00:02:29,975 --> 00:02:31,107
[CHUCKLES]

47
00:02:39,202 --> 00:02:41,335
PATTY:  <i>Patty Lane,</i><i>
one small woman</i>

48
00:02:41,465 --> 00:02:44,425
<i>fighting the mighty for</i>
<i>the rights of the little guy.</i>

49
00:02:44,555 --> 00:02:45,904
<i>You go, girl!</i>

50
00:02:49,125 --> 00:02:50,909
Now I'm really
 depressing myself.

51
00:02:51,040 --> 00:02:52,476
<i>[THE PATTY DUKE SHOW</i>
 THEME SONG PLAYING]

52
00:03:56,801 --> 00:04:00,805
Hey, dad. Read your story
 in this morning's paper.

53
00:04:00,936 --> 00:04:04,461
Do you realize that you used
 the phrase "alleged cover-up"
 five times?

54
00:04:04,592 --> 00:04:06,028
Only five times?

55
00:04:06,158 --> 00:04:08,857
I guess that's why
 they consider me
 pro-administration.

56
00:04:08,987 --> 00:04:10,162
[LAUGHING]

57
00:04:10,946 --> 00:04:12,164
Mom called from Auckland.

58
00:04:12,295 --> 00:04:14,515
Her story's keeping her there
 through next week.

59
00:04:14,645 --> 00:04:16,299
Between her schedule
 and mine...

60
00:04:16,430 --> 00:04:19,346
BOTH: It's a miracle
 we got together long
 enough to have you.

61
00:04:19,476 --> 00:04:20,738
You've heard that one, huh?

62
00:04:20,869 --> 00:04:22,392
-A few times.
-[DOOR OPENING]

63
00:04:22,523 --> 00:04:24,220
MARTIN: Hello? Hello?

64
00:04:24,351 --> 00:04:25,613
Grandma! Grandpa!

65
00:04:25,743 --> 00:04:27,092
How are you? Good to see you.

66
00:04:27,223 --> 00:04:30,226
-Need a hand, Ross?
-No, I got it. Thanks.

67
00:04:30,357 --> 00:04:32,228
-How was your flight?
 -Fine.

68
00:04:32,359 --> 00:04:34,970
If you don't mind sitting
 in the last row
 next to the bathroom,

69
00:04:35,100 --> 00:04:36,885
watching all those
 desperate people.

70
00:04:37,015 --> 00:04:38,843
[ALL LAUGHING]

71
00:04:38,974 --> 00:04:42,107
Senior citizen seats
 are the next best thing
 to sitting on the wings.

72
00:04:42,238 --> 00:04:43,848
Is Patty hip to
 what's happening yet?

73
00:04:43,979 --> 00:04:47,330
No. Totally clueless.
 She's gonna freak
 when she finds out.

74
00:04:47,461 --> 00:04:49,289
I can't wait to tell her.

75
00:04:49,419 --> 00:04:52,727
Natalie, it's supposed
 to be a surprise.

76
00:04:52,857 --> 00:04:55,338
Telling your mother
 a secret is like
 putting it on the internet.

77
00:04:56,644 --> 00:04:58,559
Dad! Mom!

78
00:04:58,689 --> 00:04:59,951
Honey!

79
00:05:00,082 --> 00:05:03,041
Oh! What a good surprise!

80
00:05:03,172 --> 00:05:05,000
[GASPING]
 What are you doing here?

81
00:05:05,130 --> 00:05:08,264
Oh, we were so excited
 when we heard the news,
 we had to be here for...

82
00:05:08,395 --> 00:05:09,787
Alumni week.

83
00:05:10,440 --> 00:05:11,398
Oh.

84
00:05:12,094 --> 00:05:13,095
Why?

85
00:05:13,225 --> 00:05:14,749
Oh, well, um,

86
00:05:14,879 --> 00:05:18,143
we knew how important
 this week was to you.

87
00:05:18,274 --> 00:05:22,496
Ah, well, you guys
 are the greatest.

88
00:05:22,626 --> 00:05:24,802
I gotta get to school.
You gonna be okay here?

89
00:05:24,933 --> 00:05:26,674
Oh, we have plenty to do.

90
00:05:26,804 --> 00:05:28,328
Ah, look up old friends...

91
00:05:28,458 --> 00:05:29,938
Spend our meager pension

92
00:05:30,068 --> 00:05:32,244
shopping for things
 your mother
 simply can't live without.

93
00:05:32,375 --> 00:05:34,638
Ah, way to go, mommo!

94
00:05:34,769 --> 00:05:36,031
All right, see you later.

95
00:05:39,817 --> 00:05:41,950
-I think we did it.
 -[SIGHS]

96
00:05:42,080 --> 00:05:44,866
Hey, you guys, I know
you're up to something,

97
00:05:44,996 --> 00:05:47,477
and I'm gonna figure out
 what it is. I always do.

98
00:05:48,086 --> 00:05:49,261
Bye.

99
00:05:50,915 --> 00:05:53,353
A wasted career.
She would've been great
in the CIA.

100
00:05:55,485 --> 00:05:57,182
So when's cousin
Cathy arriving?

101
00:05:57,313 --> 00:05:58,662
They got grounded
in Nova Scotia.

102
00:05:58,793 --> 00:06:00,403
They're not gonna be here
 till late this afternoon.

103
00:06:06,670 --> 00:06:08,193
Oh, yeah, you know,

104
00:06:08,324 --> 00:06:11,153
I'd like a strong black cup
 of coffee over here, Marge.

105
00:06:11,283 --> 00:06:12,633
By Jiminy.

106
00:06:15,375 --> 00:06:17,246
It's been a long layover.

107
00:06:18,029 --> 00:06:19,335
Excuse his manners.

108
00:06:21,642 --> 00:06:23,252
I'm trying to sound American

109
00:06:23,383 --> 00:06:25,428
so when we get there
 I'll fit right in.

110
00:06:25,559 --> 00:06:28,997
We're going to Brooklyn,
 not North Dakota.

111
00:06:29,127 --> 00:06:32,566
[AMERICAN ACCENT]
 Yo, baby, you dance
 better than I ever seen.

112
00:06:32,696 --> 00:06:36,004
[SCOTTISH ACCENT] No matter
 where we settle in the states,
 they'll think I'm a local.

113
00:06:38,180 --> 00:06:40,356
I made it clear, Liam.

114
00:06:40,487 --> 00:06:44,099
We are going for one week,
 and then back home.

115
00:06:44,229 --> 00:06:47,102
Mom, I can't take
 Scotland anymore.

116
00:06:47,232 --> 00:06:49,321
The only exciting thing
that ever happens there

117
00:06:49,452 --> 00:06:53,064
is when a cold wind
 blows someone's kilt
 into their face.

118
00:06:53,195 --> 00:06:57,417
All you know about America
is from TV and movies.

119
00:06:57,547 --> 00:07:00,245
You'll quickly realize
 how different things are.

120
00:07:01,682 --> 00:07:03,727
You love America, too.

121
00:07:03,858 --> 00:07:05,294
I know you miss dad.

122
00:07:05,425 --> 00:07:06,948
But it's time.

123
00:07:07,078 --> 00:07:09,603
You need this trip.
 And so do I.

124
00:07:11,692 --> 00:07:15,043
How did I ever get
a clever son like you?

125
00:07:15,173 --> 00:07:18,612
Genetics, pure and simple.

126
00:07:18,742 --> 00:07:21,005
WOMAN: [ON PA]
<i>Transworld flight from</i>
<i>Edinburgh to New York City</i>

127
00:07:21,136 --> 00:07:23,355
<i>is now ready for</i><i>
re-boarding at gate 7</i>.

128
00:07:23,486 --> 00:07:25,967
Look out, New York.
 Here we come.

129
00:07:35,324 --> 00:07:36,586
Thanks! Have a good day.

130
00:07:36,717 --> 00:07:37,892
You too.

131
00:07:48,468 --> 00:07:49,643
[SIGHS]

132
00:07:50,731 --> 00:07:51,906
Hi.

133
00:08:00,784 --> 00:08:02,743
Yes, fine,
 I'll take care of it.
 Thank you.

134
00:08:02,873 --> 00:08:04,092
[TELEPHONE RINGING]

135
00:08:04,919 --> 00:08:06,050
Morning, Miss Lane.

136
00:08:06,181 --> 00:08:07,312
-Mr. Sweeney.
 -Mmm.

137
00:08:09,314 --> 00:08:11,534
The mayor. City council...

138
00:08:11,665 --> 00:08:15,320
Still tying up our fax lines
 with your incessant missives
 to our elected officials, huh?

139
00:08:15,451 --> 00:08:18,802
They have to be reminded
 that our school is a landmark.

140
00:08:18,933 --> 00:08:20,108
Uh-huh.

141
00:08:20,238 --> 00:08:23,154
And essential to the survival
 of our community.

142
00:08:23,285 --> 00:08:26,288
Miss Lane, I know
you don't enjoy this
concept called reality,

143
00:08:26,418 --> 00:08:28,420
-but this "landmark"
has no heat,
-[BELL RINGING]

144
00:08:28,551 --> 00:08:30,858
the plumbing is almost
non-existent...

145
00:08:30,988 --> 00:08:35,340
[SQUEAKY VOICE]
 Will all students please
 proceed to their homerooms.

146
00:08:35,471 --> 00:08:39,562
SWEENEY: And the PA system
 makes everybody sound
 like they ingested helium.

147
00:08:39,693 --> 00:08:42,826
We're gonna make
 a lot of money
 during alumni week.

148
00:08:42,957 --> 00:08:45,133
[SIGHS]
 A half a million dollars,
 Miss Lane.

149
00:08:45,263 --> 00:08:48,179
Do you really think
 you can raise that kind
 of money in one week

150
00:08:48,310 --> 00:08:52,053
with a basketball game,
 a play, and an arts
 and crafts fair?

151
00:08:52,183 --> 00:08:55,360
You left out
 the celebrity concert
 and dance.

152
00:08:55,491 --> 00:08:59,974
Oh, yes, that's right.
 The one without
 the celebrities.

153
00:09:00,104 --> 00:09:02,629
All right.
So not everybody
has confirmed.

154
00:09:02,759 --> 00:09:04,805
I'm working on it.

155
00:09:04,935 --> 00:09:10,462
You also forget we have
 a lot of wealthy alums who can
 potentially write big checks.

156
00:09:10,593 --> 00:09:13,465
Miss Lane,
 what you're talking about
 is basically impossible.

157
00:09:13,596 --> 00:09:15,685
I love starting
 with the basics.

158
00:09:19,602 --> 00:09:21,517
Okay. Before we start
the rehearsal,

159
00:09:21,648 --> 00:09:24,781
we're gonna do
 an acting warm-up exercise.

160
00:09:24,912 --> 00:09:26,087
Everybody on your feet.

161
00:09:27,218 --> 00:09:29,525
Let's go. Come on.

162
00:09:29,656 --> 00:09:34,661
All right.
 We're going to use
 creative imagery.

163
00:09:35,444 --> 00:09:37,272
Close your eyes...

164
00:09:38,186 --> 00:09:39,230
Separate.

165
00:09:39,361 --> 00:09:40,536
[ALL LAUGHING]

166
00:09:41,798 --> 00:09:43,931
And no sleeping.

167
00:09:45,106 --> 00:09:50,546
Now feel your body expand...

168
00:09:50,677 --> 00:09:51,895
[ALL LAUGHING]

169
00:09:52,374 --> 00:09:54,855
Fill the space.

170
00:09:56,857 --> 00:09:59,381
Fill the room.

171
00:10:01,383 --> 00:10:04,473
Fill the school.

172
00:10:04,604 --> 00:10:06,562
Fill Brooklyn.

173
00:10:06,693 --> 00:10:08,651
Don't fill the hallways.

174
00:10:08,782 --> 00:10:09,739
[ALL LAUGHING]

175
00:10:09,870 --> 00:10:11,393
And Miss Lane rules!

176
00:10:12,960 --> 00:10:15,310
Yeah, well, let's make sure
she keeps her job.

177
00:10:15,440 --> 00:10:18,748
We only have three days
 left to pull
<i>Romeo and Juliet</i>together.

178
00:10:18,879 --> 00:10:21,446
Let's start with act two,
 scene one.

179
00:10:21,577 --> 00:10:22,709
Scene two.

180
00:10:24,145 --> 00:10:25,625
Tiffany? Anthony?

181
00:10:26,321 --> 00:10:27,409
Tiffany?

182
00:10:29,193 --> 00:10:31,718
ALL: Whoo-hoo!

183
00:10:35,765 --> 00:10:37,724
Could we save that
for the scene?

184
00:10:37,854 --> 00:10:38,986
Sorry, Miss Lane.

185
00:10:40,814 --> 00:10:41,989
Begin.

186
00:10:43,555 --> 00:10:47,298
Yo, Romeo, Romeo,
 wherefore art thou, Romeo?

187
00:10:47,429 --> 00:10:49,605
Deny thy father
 and refuse thy name.

188
00:10:49,736 --> 00:10:51,215
[TELEPHONE RINGING]

189
00:10:56,090 --> 00:10:58,092
No one's at home.

190
00:10:58,222 --> 00:11:01,225
They must not have got
 the message that we switched
 planes and got in early.

191
00:11:01,356 --> 00:11:02,966
Now what?

192
00:11:03,097 --> 00:11:06,666
Now we take a taxi
 and surprise Patty at school.

193
00:11:10,670 --> 00:11:12,149
This wall is gone.

194
00:11:12,280 --> 00:11:14,325
These moldings,
 they all got to go.

195
00:11:14,456 --> 00:11:17,546
And that, whatever that is,
 that's definitely gotta go.

196
00:11:23,204 --> 00:11:24,901
It's so old.

197
00:11:25,032 --> 00:11:27,121
Old can be nice, Liam.

198
00:11:28,122 --> 00:11:29,819
Sometimes.

199
00:11:29,950 --> 00:11:32,517
Uh, good afternoon, everyone.

200
00:11:32,648 --> 00:11:35,695
This will be a difficult...
 Excuse me, Miss O'Halloran...

201
00:11:35,825 --> 00:11:38,872
Be a difficult meeting,
I'm afraid.

202
00:11:39,002 --> 00:11:41,613
We have to deal
 with the real possibility

203
00:11:41,744 --> 00:11:45,269
that come next semester,
this school will close.

204
00:11:45,400 --> 00:11:48,316
All the students will be
 dispersed to other schools,

205
00:11:48,446 --> 00:11:52,146
and unfortunately,
 many of you will be let go.

206
00:11:52,276 --> 00:11:56,498
On the upside, some of you are
 eligible for early retirement.

207
00:11:56,628 --> 00:11:59,327
This is outrageous!
Where's Patty?

208
00:12:01,721 --> 00:12:03,287
Hey!

209
00:12:03,418 --> 00:12:06,377
Who authorized
 you people to be in here?

210
00:12:06,508 --> 00:12:09,641
All we are doing, lady,
 is a structural
 feasibility study

211
00:12:09,772 --> 00:12:11,818
for Mrs. Caldwell,
 all right?

212
00:12:11,948 --> 00:12:14,734
SWEENEY: If there
 are no other questions...

213
00:12:14,864 --> 00:12:17,911
Ah, Miss Lane.
 Finally decided
 to join us, hmm?

214
00:12:19,303 --> 00:12:20,914
Excuse me?

215
00:12:21,044 --> 00:12:22,872
Yeah, please.
 Could you kindly take
 a seat so we can continue.

216
00:12:23,003 --> 00:12:25,266
Oh, I'm not...

217
00:12:25,396 --> 00:12:27,747
Miss Lane, please!

218
00:12:34,666 --> 00:12:36,581
Thank you. Now.

219
00:12:36,712 --> 00:12:40,237
Although this facility
 will cease to exist
 as a school,

220
00:12:40,368 --> 00:12:42,283
it will not be demolished.

221
00:12:42,413 --> 00:12:44,111
[CLEARS THROAT] To explain,

222
00:12:44,241 --> 00:12:46,983
a community leader
and developer,

223
00:12:47,114 --> 00:12:49,072
Sue Ellen Caldwell.

224
00:12:49,203 --> 00:12:50,378
[APPLAUSE]

225
00:12:58,429 --> 00:13:00,475
-Yes, so I've got...
 -Yes, thank you.

226
00:13:00,605 --> 00:13:02,303
Yes, thank you.

227
00:13:02,433 --> 00:13:03,652
Well...

228
00:13:03,783 --> 00:13:05,828
Good afternoon, friends.

229
00:13:05,959 --> 00:13:08,613
First of all, I would like to
 thank principal Sweeney

230
00:13:08,744 --> 00:13:12,661
for asking me here today
 so that I might
 have this opportunity

231
00:13:12,792 --> 00:13:16,752
to explain to you all
 exactly what's going on.

232
00:13:16,883 --> 00:13:20,538
Therefore, I am
 pleased to announce

233
00:13:20,669 --> 00:13:24,891
that I have signed
 a tentative agreement
 to buy this property,

234
00:13:25,021 --> 00:13:26,501
but only in the event

235
00:13:26,631 --> 00:13:30,157
that the school is unable
 to raise the money necessary

236
00:13:30,287 --> 00:13:33,116
to keep this place going
 as an institute of learning.

237
00:13:33,247 --> 00:13:34,639
Now not to worry!

238
00:13:34,770 --> 00:13:38,382
I have no intention
 of destroying this edifice,

239
00:13:38,513 --> 00:13:42,038
only modifying
its function. Slightly.

240
00:13:42,169 --> 00:13:46,521
Mrs. Caldwell doesn't
own this building.
The city does.

241
00:13:46,651 --> 00:13:49,045
That's never stopped
 Mrs. C before, right, boys?

242
00:13:49,176 --> 00:13:50,960
[LAUGHING]

243
00:13:51,091 --> 00:13:52,919
Yeah, well,
 it's gonna this time.

244
00:13:53,049 --> 00:13:55,008
You are trespassing.
 Please leave.

245
00:13:55,138 --> 00:13:56,531
Hey! Put down
 those blueprints!

246
00:13:56,661 --> 00:13:58,141
We got a job
to do here, all right?

247
00:13:58,272 --> 00:13:59,621
Fine. Do it someplace else.

248
00:13:59,751 --> 00:14:01,275
You can't do that!

249
00:14:02,058 --> 00:14:03,320
Uh-oh.

250
00:14:03,451 --> 00:14:05,496
SUE ELLEN:
 The Brooklyn Heights Mall

251
00:14:05,627 --> 00:14:08,543
will retain
 this beautiful structure.

252
00:14:08,673 --> 00:14:12,677
And in keeping
 with our school's
 reputation for excellence,

253
00:14:12,808 --> 00:14:17,421
we'll have only
the finest retail merchants
in the business.

254
00:14:17,552 --> 00:14:20,511
Names like, Luggage World,

255
00:14:21,599 --> 00:14:23,775
Vickie's nighties,

256
00:14:23,906 --> 00:14:28,389
and the Roger Corman
 Studio Store.

257
00:14:29,999 --> 00:14:31,827
-Hey!
 -MAN: I've heard enough.

258
00:14:31,958 --> 00:14:34,917
You're our
 representative, Patty.
 Everybody's counting on you.

259
00:14:35,048 --> 00:14:37,398
-But I'm not...
 -Yes, Miss Lane?

260
00:14:37,528 --> 00:14:39,617
MAN: Miss Lane, please.

261
00:14:39,748 --> 00:14:40,836
Well, I...

262
00:14:42,272 --> 00:14:45,232
-I think...
 -Yes. Go!

263
00:14:45,362 --> 00:14:49,714
I just think that
what you're proposing
is disgusting.

264
00:14:49,845 --> 00:14:51,238
[ALL APPLAUDING]

265
00:14:55,677 --> 00:14:56,983
MAN: Good point, Patty.

266
00:14:57,113 --> 00:15:01,161
When our institutions
 no longer matter,

267
00:15:01,291 --> 00:15:03,163
we no longer matter.

268
00:15:03,990 --> 00:15:05,556
MAN: Hear, hear!

269
00:15:05,687 --> 00:15:09,778
For they have formed
 the way we look at the world.

270
00:15:09,909 --> 00:15:11,823
Oh, please.

271
00:15:13,129 --> 00:15:16,480
This school hasn't
 just shaped a neighborhood.

272
00:15:16,611 --> 00:15:20,615
It has shaped the way
 a neighborhood sees itself.

273
00:15:20,745 --> 00:15:23,444
Mrs. Caldwell is not
 going to be happy about this.

274
00:15:23,574 --> 00:15:26,838
Mrs. Caldwell hasn't been
 happy since she
 evicted a building

275
00:15:26,969 --> 00:15:28,797
full of senior citizens
in a blizzard.

276
00:15:28,928 --> 00:15:30,233
After you.

277
00:15:38,720 --> 00:15:40,287
My meeting!

278
00:15:40,417 --> 00:15:42,593
Excuse me! Pardon me!

279
00:15:42,724 --> 00:15:45,335
If we turn our backs
 on Brooklyn Heights high,

280
00:15:46,510 --> 00:15:48,469
we turn our backs
 on ourselves.

281
00:15:48,599 --> 00:15:49,949
[ALL APPLAUDING]

282
00:16:20,892 --> 00:16:22,198
[INDISTINCT]

283
00:16:23,417 --> 00:16:24,896
Sue Ellen!

284
00:16:25,027 --> 00:16:27,812
[SIGHS]
 Well, you haven't learned,
 have you, Patty?

285
00:16:27,943 --> 00:16:31,599
When you go up against me,
 you always lose.

286
00:16:31,729 --> 00:16:33,731
Should have stuck
with the other outfit,

287
00:16:33,862 --> 00:16:35,342
thrift store girl.

288
00:16:37,909 --> 00:16:40,390
Why couldn't I listen to Pablo
 and learn to value of thrift?

289
00:16:43,741 --> 00:16:45,134
Thrift...

290
00:16:46,092 --> 00:16:47,528
That's it.

291
00:16:47,658 --> 00:16:50,096
I'll go to the thrift shop.
 I'm sure to find a gown there.

292
00:16:51,488 --> 00:16:54,535
-It's me.
-It is lovely.

293
00:16:54,665 --> 00:16:57,190
You're lucky. It came in
 just a little while ago.

294
00:16:57,320 --> 00:16:59,148
Oh?

295
00:16:59,279 --> 00:17:02,891
So you went to the thrift shop
 and bought my old dress?

296
00:17:03,022 --> 00:17:04,284
I did not!

297
00:17:07,417 --> 00:17:09,463
Well, I didn't know
 it was your dress.

298
00:17:10,855 --> 00:17:12,901
Please, Sue, promise me
you won't tell anybody.

299
00:17:13,032 --> 00:17:15,556
Please? Promise?
 Buddy, pal, friend...

300
00:17:15,686 --> 00:17:17,688
Hmm, of course not.

301
00:17:17,819 --> 00:17:19,821
I'd be an utter monster to.

302
00:17:20,822 --> 00:17:23,738
You made us proud, Patty.

303
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:27,916
I like your hair back better.

304
00:18:13,570 --> 00:18:14,745
[GASPING]

305
00:18:16,834 --> 00:18:18,184
Cathy!

306
00:18:20,534 --> 00:18:23,058
-Patty!
 -You look great!

307
00:18:25,582 --> 00:18:26,757
[SIGHS]

308
00:18:33,460 --> 00:18:34,548
[LAUGHTER]

309
00:18:35,679 --> 00:18:38,595
Oh, I still can't believe
 you guys are here.

310
00:18:38,726 --> 00:18:42,599
You know the last time
 I saw you, you barely
 came up to my waist.

311
00:18:42,730 --> 00:18:44,949
And so handsome.

312
00:18:45,080 --> 00:18:47,343
I prefer hip, cool,
 out of sight.

313
00:18:47,474 --> 00:18:49,650
Oh. You got it.

314
00:18:49,780 --> 00:18:52,653
I told mom if she didn't come,
 I'd fed-ex myself in a box,

315
00:18:52,783 --> 00:18:54,045
like I did to London.

316
00:18:54,742 --> 00:18:57,136
You went to London in a box?

317
00:18:57,266 --> 00:19:00,269
Actually, it broke
 when they were loading
 me in the truck in Glasgow.

318
00:19:01,923 --> 00:19:04,143
That sounds like something
 our Patty might have done.

319
00:19:04,273 --> 00:19:05,492
Is it cool to show
 Liam my room?

320
00:19:05,622 --> 00:19:06,841
Of course.

321
00:19:06,971 --> 00:19:08,408
Here's a scary thought.

322
00:19:08,538 --> 00:19:11,933
It's the same room your mom
 and my grandma used to share.

323
00:19:12,063 --> 00:19:14,022
I didn't know families
 in America kept the same house

324
00:19:14,153 --> 00:19:15,850
from one generation
 to the next.

325
00:19:15,980 --> 00:19:19,332
Well, the previous owners
 made me an offer
 I couldn't refuse.

326
00:19:19,462 --> 00:19:21,943
The monthly rent check
 keeps her mother
 in lottery tickets.

327
00:19:22,291 --> 00:19:23,466
[ALL LAUGHING]

328
00:19:24,337 --> 00:19:26,295
Mom, I can do that.

329
00:19:26,426 --> 00:19:30,386
So can I.
And so can your father.

330
00:19:30,517 --> 00:19:32,649
This is one of
the disadvantages
of retirement.

331
00:19:32,780 --> 00:19:34,999
You retire to have
nothing to do.

332
00:19:35,130 --> 00:19:37,567
So why does everyone
 think you need
 to do something?

333
00:19:37,698 --> 00:19:40,353
All right, all right,
 it's just a question.

334
00:19:40,483 --> 00:19:42,050
I didn't expect an answer.

335
00:19:44,487 --> 00:19:46,054
Please say something
to your mother.

336
00:19:46,185 --> 00:19:47,273
Oh... [GIGGLING]

337
00:19:48,230 --> 00:19:49,710
They haven't changed.

338
00:19:49,840 --> 00:19:50,972
They've gotten worse.

339
00:19:52,626 --> 00:19:54,367
Gee, I'm sorry I haven't
called you much lately.

340
00:19:54,497 --> 00:19:57,239
Oh, things have been
 so hectic at school.

341
00:19:57,370 --> 00:20:01,069
I'm afraid I've become
 a bit of a hermit
 since Colin died.

342
00:20:01,200 --> 00:20:02,375
Well, let's face it, Cath.

343
00:20:02,505 --> 00:20:05,116
You never were
much of a party animal.

344
00:20:05,247 --> 00:20:07,336
My world revolves
 around Liam now.

345
00:20:08,424 --> 00:20:09,860
He keeps me quite busy.

346
00:20:09,991 --> 00:20:11,688
Yeah, I know what you mean.

347
00:20:11,819 --> 00:20:15,257
Michael and Nancy are
 usually off chasing a story

348
00:20:15,388 --> 00:20:18,042
and Molly lives here more than
 she does at her own house.

349
00:20:18,956 --> 00:20:20,131
And I love it.

350
00:20:23,222 --> 00:20:26,181
It's a little sad,
 thinking of them grown up

351
00:20:26,312 --> 00:20:27,835
and not needing us anymore.

352
00:20:29,097 --> 00:20:30,577
They'll always need us, Cath.

353
00:20:32,013 --> 00:20:33,493
Then when we're really old,

354
00:20:33,623 --> 00:20:35,669
we'll check into
the same nursing home,

355
00:20:35,799 --> 00:20:37,584
and give them a run
 for their money.

356
00:20:37,714 --> 00:20:38,802
[CHUCKLES]

357
00:20:40,456 --> 00:20:42,893
You should have seen
 Sue Ellen's face

358
00:20:43,024 --> 00:20:44,199
when I was making that speech.

359
00:20:44,330 --> 00:20:46,636
She could have
 killed me... You.

360
00:20:48,203 --> 00:20:50,031
Yeah, well, she's lucky
it wasn't me.

361
00:20:50,161 --> 00:20:52,076
I wouldn't have
been so polite.

362
00:20:52,207 --> 00:20:55,254
It's like old times.
People mixing us up...

363
00:20:56,690 --> 00:20:59,649
Do you have any idea
 what a weapon we have
 on our hands?

364
00:20:59,780 --> 00:21:01,608
What do you mean?

365
00:21:01,738 --> 00:21:03,871
Separately, we're two girls
who have a few talents.

366
00:21:04,001 --> 00:21:05,394
Just like anyone else.

367
00:21:05,525 --> 00:21:07,527
You're a brain. I like sports.

368
00:21:07,657 --> 00:21:10,094
You like opera.
 I like to dance.

369
00:21:10,225 --> 00:21:12,140
But together,
 we're really on the beam.

370
00:21:13,097 --> 00:21:14,142
On the beam?

371
00:21:14,273 --> 00:21:15,622
With it.

372
00:21:15,752 --> 00:21:18,277
We can be in two different
 places at the same time.

373
00:21:18,407 --> 00:21:20,496
Do you think we could
 really fool people, Patty?

374
00:21:21,541 --> 00:21:22,716
Let's find out.

375
00:21:22,846 --> 00:21:23,934
How?

376
00:21:25,153 --> 00:21:26,154
Any objections?

377
00:21:26,285 --> 00:21:27,373
Not in the least.

378
00:21:30,854 --> 00:21:33,292
[ENGLISH ACCENT] I think I
 will descend below and inquire

379
00:21:33,422 --> 00:21:35,903
how Aunt Natalie
 and dear Uncle Martin
 are getting along.

380
00:21:36,033 --> 00:21:37,121
[BOTH LAUGHING]

381
00:21:38,427 --> 00:21:39,515
That we did.

382
00:21:40,647 --> 00:21:42,083
Hmm.

383
00:21:42,213 --> 00:21:45,782
MOLLY: That's Stone Adams.
He's my favorite actor.

384
00:21:45,913 --> 00:21:48,350
I wouldn't mind having
 his luck with the babes.

385
00:21:49,612 --> 00:21:51,397
My grandma taught him
 English and drama.

386
00:21:52,223 --> 00:21:53,964
That's radical.

387
00:21:54,095 --> 00:21:56,924
You know, I've always
loved things American.

388
00:21:57,054 --> 00:21:58,882
I'd love to see Scotland.

389
00:21:59,013 --> 00:22:01,363
I'd love to see anywhere
 that isn't Brooklyn.

390
00:22:01,494 --> 00:22:03,496
You're mad!

391
00:22:03,626 --> 00:22:06,629
Brooklyn, as they say
 in the local vernacular,

392
00:22:06,760 --> 00:22:09,763
is the grenade.

393
00:22:11,460 --> 00:22:12,679
Do you mean, the bomb?

394
00:22:13,723 --> 00:22:14,942
That, too.

395
00:22:18,293 --> 00:22:20,600
MOLLY: Save our school.
 Five bucks a chance.

396
00:22:21,252 --> 00:22:22,732
You win a motor scooter.

397
00:22:23,559 --> 00:22:24,821
Only five bucks.

398
00:22:26,519 --> 00:22:27,694
[UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING]

399
00:22:30,740 --> 00:22:31,959
[BOYS WHISTLING]

400
00:22:35,919 --> 00:22:37,660
Way to go, guys! Yeah!

401
00:22:43,971 --> 00:22:45,712
I told you this place
 would be a morgue.

402
00:22:45,842 --> 00:22:48,192
Yes, you did, Normann.
 But I still don't want to
 take the chance

403
00:22:48,323 --> 00:22:52,022
that by some pathetic
 accident, Patty's able to
 raise the money.

404
00:22:52,153 --> 00:22:55,939
So I want to put
 all our contingency plans
 into effect.

405
00:22:56,070 --> 00:22:57,463
You know what to do, Normann.

406
00:23:02,337 --> 00:23:04,774
What happened
 to all the fans?

407
00:23:04,905 --> 00:23:07,864
Makes no sense.
 Paper said it was
 gonna be a sell-out.

408
00:23:07,995 --> 00:23:09,736
Well, a lot of people
 are coming from out of town.

409
00:23:09,866 --> 00:23:11,215
Maybe they got stuck
 in traffic.

410
00:23:14,305 --> 00:23:17,091
I can't sit here anymore.
 Popcorn anyone?

411
00:23:17,221 --> 00:23:18,658
Lots of salt, extra butter.

412
00:23:18,788 --> 00:23:20,877
-Cherry coke?
 -No ice.

413
00:23:21,008 --> 00:23:22,792
[AMERICAN ACCENT]
 Yo! What's up? Wanna party?

414
00:23:22,923 --> 00:23:23,880
Not with you.

415
00:23:24,011 --> 00:23:25,839
You're not exactly
 helping me here.

416
00:23:29,669 --> 00:23:31,714
I've always been able
 to draw a crowd.

417
00:23:31,845 --> 00:23:33,412
This is how we do it
 back home.

418
00:23:38,460 --> 00:23:39,809
[SCOTTISH MUSIC PLAYING]

419
00:23:57,218 --> 00:23:58,785
[ONLOOKERS CLAPPING TO MUSIC]

420
00:24:25,638 --> 00:24:26,726
[ALL CHEERING]

421
00:24:28,118 --> 00:24:30,556
-Look. You did good.
 -Cool. Told you.

422
00:24:30,686 --> 00:24:31,905
Thank you.

423
00:24:32,340 --> 00:24:34,168
Ahh! Oh!

424
00:24:34,298 --> 00:24:36,083
Careful, Patty, careful.

425
00:24:36,213 --> 00:24:37,563
The cleaning bill
for this outfit

426
00:24:37,693 --> 00:24:39,869
would cost more than
 your entire wardrobe.

427
00:24:40,000 --> 00:24:42,263
That's because
 they charge double
 for extra smells.

428
00:24:42,393 --> 00:24:46,093
Ooh, I'm so glad
 we've managed to stay
 enemies all these years.

429
00:24:46,223 --> 00:24:48,965
I thrive on
the tension, don't you?

430
00:24:49,096 --> 00:24:52,491
This is your alma mater
as much as it is mine.

431
00:24:52,621 --> 00:24:54,318
Why do you want to destroy it?

432
00:24:54,449 --> 00:24:57,278
Patty, Patty, Patty. It's old.

433
00:24:57,408 --> 00:25:01,108
Its time has come and gone.
 A little like you, dear.

434
00:25:04,807 --> 00:25:08,376
Wow. You know,
 I love Brooklyn.

435
00:25:08,507 --> 00:25:11,988
I'm totally happy for you,
 but I didn't sell one ticket.

436
00:25:12,119 --> 00:25:14,469
What? You got a customer
 right here.

437
00:25:16,950 --> 00:25:18,647
I'll take $30 worth.

438
00:25:19,300 --> 00:25:20,823
[CAR HORN HONKING]

439
00:25:20,954 --> 00:25:22,259
Hey, Richard!

440
00:25:26,829 --> 00:25:29,484
-Patty...
 -Richard, I need a favor.

441
00:25:29,615 --> 00:25:32,269
Stop me before I commit
 justifiable homicide.

442
00:25:32,400 --> 00:25:35,403
Sue Ellen.
 You can't let her get to you.

443
00:25:35,534 --> 00:25:39,015
The woman is miserable.
 She's been married five times.

444
00:25:39,146 --> 00:25:41,191
So, she's been with
 four more men than I have.

445
00:25:41,322 --> 00:25:42,584
[CHUCKLES]

446
00:25:42,715 --> 00:25:45,326
I'm not that far
 ahead of you.

447
00:25:45,456 --> 00:25:48,068
After all, we were
 married for 27 years.

448
00:25:48,198 --> 00:25:51,027
Are you still seeing, um,
 what's-her-name?

449
00:25:51,158 --> 00:25:55,205
Rebecca? Nah,
she wore too many hats.

450
00:25:55,336 --> 00:25:58,121
I think I saw her hair
 maybe, uh, twice.

451
00:25:58,644 --> 00:26:00,733
Are you dating?

452
00:26:00,863 --> 00:26:02,082
I met someone
 on the internet.

453
00:26:02,212 --> 00:26:03,387
Really?

454
00:26:03,518 --> 00:26:05,172
I finally got the courage
 to meet him.

455
00:26:05,302 --> 00:26:07,304
He was old enough
 to be my dad's dad.

456
00:26:07,435 --> 00:26:08,784
Good typist, though.

457
00:26:11,352 --> 00:26:13,702
Thanks.
 For helping with the set.

458
00:26:15,008 --> 00:26:16,313
Patty, I...

459
00:26:19,273 --> 00:26:21,928
We're gonna keep
 the school going, somehow.

460
00:26:25,192 --> 00:26:26,323
Thanks.

461
00:26:46,517 --> 00:26:47,693
[GRUNTING]

462
00:26:51,522 --> 00:26:52,698
Ugh!

463
00:27:10,150 --> 00:27:11,238
[SCREAMS]

464
00:27:12,587 --> 00:27:14,067
Oh! Oh! Oh!

465
00:27:17,374 --> 00:27:18,549
[CHUCKLING]

466
00:27:41,616 --> 00:27:42,530
Patty?

467
00:27:42,661 --> 00:27:43,923
Oh!

468
00:27:44,053 --> 00:27:45,446
Hi, Cath.

469
00:27:45,576 --> 00:27:46,926
I didn't hear you come in.

470
00:27:48,275 --> 00:27:49,885
I just needed
some down time.

471
00:27:52,801 --> 00:27:56,196
The old room looks different,
 but somehow
 it's still the same.

472
00:27:57,284 --> 00:27:58,415
Kind of like us.

473
00:27:59,460 --> 00:28:01,244
Uh, pardon, me.
 Am I interrupting?

474
00:28:02,289 --> 00:28:03,377
Yeah.

475
00:28:03,943 --> 00:28:05,640
Well, anyhow...

476
00:28:05,771 --> 00:28:08,861
Michael and I got talking
 about the strange
 turnout tonight.

477
00:28:09,600 --> 00:28:10,689
So I did some digging.

478
00:28:11,254 --> 00:28:12,995
Digging?

479
00:28:13,126 --> 00:28:15,911
I may have retired,
 but the newspaperman
 inside me didn't.

480
00:28:16,042 --> 00:28:17,913
I asked around,
and guess what?

481
00:28:18,044 --> 00:28:21,830
Somebody hacked into
the computerized
ticket system.

482
00:28:21,961 --> 00:28:24,180
Whenever anybody tried
 to buy tickets for the game,

483
00:28:24,311 --> 00:28:26,574
the computer showed
 that it was sold out.

484
00:28:26,705 --> 00:28:28,837
You don't want that
 to happen at the art fair.

485
00:28:28,968 --> 00:28:31,187
So the question is,
who in their right mind

486
00:28:31,318 --> 00:28:33,189
would want to
sabotage you that way?

487
00:28:34,147 --> 00:28:36,192
Well, I know who.

488
00:28:36,323 --> 00:28:39,979
But the last word I'd use
 to describe her mind is right.

489
00:28:40,806 --> 00:28:42,546
She wouldn't.

490
00:28:42,677 --> 00:28:43,983
Who else?

491
00:28:44,113 --> 00:28:45,680
Well, what are we going to do?

492
00:28:46,681 --> 00:28:48,204
"We"?

493
00:28:48,335 --> 00:28:50,729
You don't think I'm going
 to let you be the only hero.

494
00:28:51,468 --> 00:28:52,556
[GIGGLING]

495
00:28:58,388 --> 00:28:59,825
[INDISTINCT]

496
00:29:04,786 --> 00:29:05,831
Molly...

497
00:29:10,966 --> 00:29:13,708
I've been thinking,
 and I'm not advocating this,

498
00:29:13,839 --> 00:29:16,580
I'm just saying that I bet

499
00:29:16,711 --> 00:29:19,409
a person who's
 good with computers

500
00:29:19,540 --> 00:29:21,760
could beat Sue Ellen
at her own dirty game.

501
00:29:22,586 --> 00:29:23,631
You think?

502
00:29:34,947 --> 00:29:36,383
-I'm in.
-Good.

503
00:29:41,605 --> 00:29:44,130
Sue Ellen Caldwell,
daily calendar.

504
00:29:44,260 --> 00:29:47,046
She'll be pushing up daisies
 by the time we're through.

505
00:29:54,227 --> 00:29:55,968
Oh, hi, Ross.

506
00:29:56,098 --> 00:29:59,754
So, you're the reason
 why Patty's tried on
 every dress she has.

507
00:29:59,885 --> 00:30:01,451
She's nervous
 about your date.

508
00:30:01,582 --> 00:30:03,236
It's not a date.

509
00:30:03,366 --> 00:30:05,934
She called and asked
 if I'd come to
 the arts and crafts fair.

510
00:30:06,065 --> 00:30:07,327
Sounds like a date to me.

511
00:30:08,197 --> 00:30:09,808
Hey, Natalie, let's go.

512
00:30:09,938 --> 00:30:11,287
-ROSS: Come on,
 we're gonna be late.
 -Watch this.

513
00:30:11,418 --> 00:30:13,812
One, two, three...

514
00:30:13,942 --> 00:30:15,988
NATALIE:
 I can't find my earring.

515
00:30:16,640 --> 00:30:18,947
Check your ear.

516
00:30:19,078 --> 00:30:22,995
In 55 years,
 she has yet to leave anywhere
 without looking for something.

517
00:30:23,125 --> 00:30:24,997
How did you know
 where it was?

518
00:30:25,127 --> 00:30:26,389
Lucky guess.

519
00:30:26,520 --> 00:30:28,391
Oh.

520
00:30:28,522 --> 00:30:30,654
-Whoa! Killer dress!
 -[ALL APPLAUDING]

521
00:30:30,785 --> 00:30:31,786
-Beautiful.
-Nice.

522
00:30:31,917 --> 00:30:34,658
Thank you.
 It was Colin's favorite.

523
00:30:34,789 --> 00:30:36,617
You look beautiful, dear.

524
00:30:36,747 --> 00:30:38,532
Thank you, Aunt Natalie.

525
00:30:38,662 --> 00:30:40,969
I feel like I just called
 everyone in the known world.

526
00:30:41,100 --> 00:30:42,928
Mom's gonna be
 so surprised when she...

527
00:30:43,929 --> 00:30:45,017
Surprised about what?

528
00:30:47,410 --> 00:30:48,890
Whoa!

529
00:30:49,021 --> 00:30:50,718
Oh, I'm not sure.

530
00:30:50,849 --> 00:30:53,503
The only thing holding it up
 is a fervent prayer.

531
00:30:53,634 --> 00:30:55,462
All right, what surprise?

532
00:30:57,856 --> 00:31:01,860
Come on, come on, you guys.
 Every time I come in a room
you clam up. What is it?

533
00:31:05,820 --> 00:31:07,866
I made Cathy's dress.

534
00:31:12,348 --> 00:31:13,393
What?

535
00:31:14,785 --> 00:31:16,918
Uh, she hasn't been out
in a long time,

536
00:31:17,049 --> 00:31:19,268
and so I thought I would
make something for her.

537
00:31:22,141 --> 00:31:23,794
Mom, you can't sew.

538
00:31:23,925 --> 00:31:27,146
-Oh, yes she can.
 She made me this tie.
 -Uh-huh.

539
00:31:28,712 --> 00:31:30,976
Big shock, huh?
Took a course.

540
00:31:32,151 --> 00:31:34,849
Richard, why don't
 we go in the den.

541
00:31:35,197 --> 00:31:36,198
Oh.

542
00:31:39,245 --> 00:31:42,378
Listen, Richard, I can see
 you still care about Patty.

543
00:31:42,509 --> 00:31:44,293
Why don't you tell her?

544
00:31:44,424 --> 00:31:47,209
She thinks of me
 as a friend or a brother.

545
00:31:47,340 --> 00:31:49,603
We were too young
 when we got married,

546
00:31:49,733 --> 00:31:51,779
and now, we're too old.

547
00:31:51,910 --> 00:31:54,564
No. I've been married
 over fifty years.

548
00:31:54,695 --> 00:31:57,916
Trust me. Love does not
recognize age.

549
00:31:58,046 --> 00:32:01,136
Took me a lot of years
 to get over the divorce.

550
00:32:01,267 --> 00:32:03,486
I've finally gotten used
 to being alone.

551
00:32:04,226 --> 00:32:06,794
Are you enjoying it?

552
00:32:06,925 --> 00:32:10,493
Pain is not something
 you wear like a badge
 of courage, Richard.

553
00:32:10,624 --> 00:32:12,017
Happiness is.

554
00:32:12,147 --> 00:32:13,279
Give that some thought.

555
00:32:16,369 --> 00:32:18,110
PATTY:
 Richard, I'm ready to go.

556
00:32:20,460 --> 00:32:21,678
[INDISTINCT TALKING]

557
00:32:27,293 --> 00:32:30,905
Martin, don't you think
this would work
in our bedroom?

558
00:32:32,385 --> 00:32:35,127
Sure, if we never
 want to fall asleep.

559
00:32:36,737 --> 00:32:38,957
[GASPS]
 There's Stone Adams' cousin!

560
00:32:39,087 --> 00:32:41,046
She can tell me
 how to get in touch
 with Stone.

561
00:32:43,526 --> 00:32:44,788
Is everything all right,
 Mrs. C?

562
00:32:44,919 --> 00:32:46,573
No, Normann,
 as a matter of fact,

563
00:32:46,703 --> 00:32:49,184
I spent a day
in the depths of hell.

564
00:32:49,315 --> 00:32:52,318
I waited an hour
 for my bankers at lunch.
 They never showed.

565
00:32:52,448 --> 00:32:54,798
Then my dental appointment
 to fix my abscessed tooth,

566
00:32:54,929 --> 00:32:57,105
which is killing me,
 was canceled.

567
00:32:57,236 --> 00:33:01,066
And the topper,
 I take my jag in for service,
 and the dealer's records

568
00:33:01,196 --> 00:33:03,068
show that I haven't made
 any payments.

569
00:33:03,198 --> 00:33:04,983
So they repossess it.

570
00:33:05,113 --> 00:33:07,898
Did you check
 your astrological chart?
 Because sometimes...

571
00:33:08,029 --> 00:33:09,074
Shut up!

572
00:33:13,208 --> 00:33:15,254
What is this?

573
00:33:15,384 --> 00:33:18,474
You were supposed to empty
 this dump before anybody had
 a chance to spend a dime!

574
00:33:19,127 --> 00:33:20,520
Yes, ma'am, I was.

575
00:33:21,564 --> 00:33:23,349
Well, do it, Normann.

576
00:33:24,176 --> 00:33:25,220
-Now!
-[STOMPS FOOT]

577
00:33:27,266 --> 00:33:29,268
Oh, goodness.

578
00:33:36,971 --> 00:33:38,103
Guess who's coming your way?

579
00:33:39,017 --> 00:33:40,496
I got the Queen O'Mean,
in sight.

580
00:33:41,236 --> 00:33:42,368
Psst!

581
00:33:45,588 --> 00:33:48,026
Psst! Ross! She's coming.

582
00:33:54,119 --> 00:33:55,729
Thank you.

583
00:33:55,859 --> 00:33:57,557
Have you sold many of these?

584
00:33:57,948 --> 00:33:58,949
Whoa!

585
00:33:59,080 --> 00:34:00,038
Hello, Sue Ellen.

586
00:34:00,168 --> 00:34:01,691
Oh, Well, hello, Mr. Lane.

587
00:34:01,822 --> 00:34:03,954
So nice to see you
supporting the school.

588
00:34:04,085 --> 00:34:06,044
Oh. Well,
as a community leader,

589
00:34:06,174 --> 00:34:08,481
I do have a certain
 sense of civic duty.

590
00:34:08,611 --> 00:34:10,265
Your father
 must be very proud.

591
00:34:10,396 --> 00:34:12,528
-Daddy?
 -We still stay in touch.

592
00:34:12,659 --> 00:34:14,182
Shall we get some punch
and chat?

593
00:34:14,313 --> 00:34:16,184
Well, actually...
Oh, all right.

594
00:34:22,060 --> 00:34:23,365
[HISSING]

595
00:34:37,423 --> 00:34:40,208
How did it go
 with Stone Adams' cousin?

596
00:34:40,339 --> 00:34:44,082
Well, it seems that
 she once sold his phone number

597
00:34:44,212 --> 00:34:45,953
to the  <i>National Enquirer,</i>

598
00:34:46,084 --> 00:34:47,955
so he doesn't keep in touch.

599
00:34:48,086 --> 00:34:49,739
[CHUCKLING]

600
00:34:49,870 --> 00:34:52,786
Oh! There's that
investment banker guy!

601
00:34:53,482 --> 00:34:54,744
He is loaded.

602
00:34:54,875 --> 00:34:55,789
He's always good for...

603
00:34:55,919 --> 00:34:57,356
Who is Stone Adams?

604
00:34:57,486 --> 00:35:00,185
Well, he's an actor.
 He's actually quite famous.

605
00:35:00,315 --> 00:35:02,491
I don't think you would have
 seen the kinds of movies
 he makes, though.

606
00:35:02,622 --> 00:35:03,927
Oh?

607
00:35:04,058 --> 00:35:07,583
Those kinds of movies?
 And Patty knows him?

608
00:35:07,714 --> 00:35:10,804
Oh! No, grandma.
 Not those kinds of movies.

609
00:35:10,934 --> 00:35:13,850
And, uh, mom knows him because
 when he was in high school,

610
00:35:13,981 --> 00:35:15,722
he was in her class.

611
00:35:15,852 --> 00:35:19,552
Well, I better rent
some of his movies and
check out his talents.

612
00:35:21,597 --> 00:35:22,729
Grandma...

613
00:35:24,557 --> 00:35:26,689
Well, it's been awfully nice,

614
00:35:26,820 --> 00:35:28,517
but I really do have
 to meet someone.

615
00:35:28,648 --> 00:35:29,649
Of course.

616
00:35:29,779 --> 00:35:32,086
Sue Ellen,
 you look hot tonight.

617
00:35:32,217 --> 00:35:33,609
What do you want?

618
00:35:33,740 --> 00:35:36,699
You know, I had this
huge crush on you
in high school,

619
00:35:36,830 --> 00:35:40,225
and it's never
 really gone away.

620
00:35:41,008 --> 00:35:42,966
Want some oysters?

621
00:35:43,097 --> 00:35:45,708
I'm pretty sure
that Normann guy
can tell you the scoop

622
00:35:45,839 --> 00:35:47,493
on the construction scandal.

623
00:35:47,623 --> 00:35:49,321
That's pretty heavy
illegal stuff.

624
00:35:49,451 --> 00:35:50,670
You think
 he was responsible?

625
00:35:50,800 --> 00:35:54,326
Maybe. In fact,
most probably.

626
00:35:54,456 --> 00:35:55,936
My editor would be
 pretty impressed if I could

627
00:35:56,066 --> 00:35:57,720
break that story
for the paper.

628
00:35:57,851 --> 00:35:59,461
I'm gonna find that Normann,

629
00:35:59,592 --> 00:36:01,594
see if I can sweat
the details out of him.

630
00:36:05,598 --> 00:36:06,599
Like it?

631
00:36:07,426 --> 00:36:08,688
Very much.

632
00:36:10,298 --> 00:36:12,387
I don't think
 I did her justice.

633
00:36:13,432 --> 00:36:14,737
Are you the artist?

634
00:36:16,696 --> 00:36:17,784
-Rock?
 -[CHUCKLING]

635
00:36:18,263 --> 00:36:19,307
Hello, Cathy.

636
00:36:21,309 --> 00:36:23,790
But I haven't used "Rock"
 since our high school days.

637
00:36:23,920 --> 00:36:25,183
It's Hank now.

638
00:36:25,618 --> 00:36:26,662
-Hank.
-Hank.

639
00:36:27,794 --> 00:36:29,448
What are you doing here?

640
00:36:29,578 --> 00:36:31,972
I heard you'd moved back
to the south of France.

641
00:36:32,102 --> 00:36:35,454
Oh, no. I've been
 living here for years now.

642
00:36:35,584 --> 00:36:39,849
That one year
 as an exchange student
 changed my life.

643
00:36:39,980 --> 00:36:43,201
I knew there was something
 familiar about this piece.

644
00:36:43,331 --> 00:36:44,550
Well, it should be familiar.

645
00:36:46,116 --> 00:36:47,379
She's you.

646
00:36:50,295 --> 00:36:51,339
You're the one that got away.

647
00:36:52,688 --> 00:36:53,950
The one I couldn't forget.

648
00:36:55,735 --> 00:36:57,040
[EXHALES]
 It was wonderful.

649
00:36:57,171 --> 00:36:58,607
[LAUGHTER]

650
00:37:00,218 --> 00:37:02,307
No kidding? What happened?

651
00:37:02,437 --> 00:37:03,960
There was a new boy
there tonight.

652
00:37:06,441 --> 00:37:08,704
He's the most
 handsome, wonderful,

653
00:37:10,532 --> 00:37:13,013
intelligent man
 I have ever seen.

654
00:37:16,538 --> 00:37:18,366
You're exactly
 as I remembered you.

655
00:37:18,497 --> 00:37:22,588
Your face still has the same
 luminous quality.

656
00:37:22,718 --> 00:37:26,113
Every expression is a direct
 conduit to your soul.

657
00:37:26,809 --> 00:37:29,029
My, you're good.

658
00:37:29,159 --> 00:37:31,727
Tell me,
 do you look these
 things up in a book

659
00:37:31,858 --> 00:37:33,512
or do you just
 make them up on the spot?

660
00:37:33,642 --> 00:37:35,427
Hey, I'm being
 totally sincere here.

661
00:37:35,949 --> 00:37:38,168
Oh.

662
00:37:38,299 --> 00:37:41,259
As a matter of fact,
 your face has gotten
 even more radiant.

663
00:37:41,389 --> 00:37:45,350
Ah, well, wrinkles,
they reflect the light.

664
00:37:48,831 --> 00:37:50,180
[DRIPPING]

665
00:37:51,573 --> 00:37:54,010
See what you do to me?
 I'm sweating here.

666
00:37:55,882 --> 00:37:58,363
You never said a word.

667
00:37:58,493 --> 00:38:02,236
You were always
 the coolest chap in school.

668
00:38:03,542 --> 00:38:04,891
Actually, I wasn't cool.

669
00:38:06,762 --> 00:38:08,721
I was shy.
Painfully shy.

670
00:38:08,851 --> 00:38:10,897
Mmm. Me, too.

671
00:38:14,857 --> 00:38:19,558
Did you ever know
 that Patty and I
 both had a crush on you?

672
00:38:20,298 --> 00:38:21,560
Wait a minute.

673
00:38:21,690 --> 00:38:24,650
Weren't the two of you
 always after the same guy?

674
00:38:24,780 --> 00:38:28,306
Oh, well,
 that did happen sometimes.

675
00:38:28,436 --> 00:38:31,309
I saw him first,
 you double-crossing
 boy-snatcher! He's mine!

676
00:38:31,439 --> 00:38:34,181
That's ridiculous! He asked
 me for a date tomorrow night!

677
00:38:34,312 --> 00:38:37,445
Oh, sure.
 After you cornered him
 and forced him to!

678
00:38:37,576 --> 00:38:39,404
LIBRARIAN: Shh!

679
00:38:39,534 --> 00:38:42,189
You told me
 he was intellectual
 and not very good looking!

680
00:38:42,320 --> 00:38:43,930
That's the way I saw him!

681
00:38:44,060 --> 00:38:46,715
You told me he was
 an athlete and handsome!

682
00:38:46,846 --> 00:38:48,326
That's the way I saw him.

683
00:38:49,022 --> 00:38:50,240
You have Richard.

684
00:38:50,371 --> 00:38:52,155
I'll trade you Richard
and two Beatle albums.

685
00:38:52,286 --> 00:38:53,243
LIBRARIAN: Shh!

686
00:38:53,374 --> 00:38:54,419
BOTH: Shh!

687
00:38:57,900 --> 00:39:00,512
ROSS: I'm so glad I had
 a chance to tell you all this,

688
00:39:00,642 --> 00:39:03,950
but I've gotta head
 for the great white way.

689
00:39:04,080 --> 00:39:06,344
But, call me sometime.

690
00:39:08,128 --> 00:39:09,912
Oh, Sue Ellen!

691
00:39:10,043 --> 00:39:13,481
I've been trying to
 get over here to
 talk to you all evening.

692
00:39:13,612 --> 00:39:17,877
Oh, Mrs. Lane.
 My, don't you look wonderful.

693
00:39:18,007 --> 00:39:21,097
It's all about
 diet and exercise.

694
00:39:21,228 --> 00:39:23,752
Let me tell you my regimen.

695
00:39:23,883 --> 00:39:27,800
Desiccated liver
 morning, noon, and night.

696
00:39:27,930 --> 00:39:29,367
Oh, you must try it.

697
00:39:30,280 --> 00:39:31,673
Would you
 excuse me, please?

698
00:39:31,804 --> 00:39:33,545
Oh. Well, of course.
 Of course.

699
00:39:37,636 --> 00:39:38,898
Can we talk?

700
00:39:39,507 --> 00:39:40,943
Excuse me.

701
00:39:41,074 --> 00:39:42,467
Not such a good night,
 Sue Ellen?

702
00:39:42,597 --> 00:39:44,469
Look, Patty, this has gotten
 all out of hand.

703
00:39:44,599 --> 00:39:46,079
Now, I'm ready
 to be reasonable.

704
00:39:46,209 --> 00:39:48,516
Ooh, I'm all for that.

705
00:39:48,647 --> 00:39:50,344
All right, how about this.

706
00:39:50,475 --> 00:39:55,915
You back off, and maybe
 I can add a few zeroes
 to your pension fund.

707
00:39:56,959 --> 00:40:00,006
Oh, please...

708
00:40:00,615 --> 00:40:02,443
Drumroll, please!

709
00:40:02,574 --> 00:40:03,836
[IMITATING DRUMROLL]

710
00:40:06,012 --> 00:40:08,536
Oh, read 'em and weep,
 Sue Ellen!

711
00:40:08,667 --> 00:40:12,018
-[ALL LAUGHING]
 -Hey, all right!

712
00:40:12,148 --> 00:40:14,324
-Congratulations, sweetheart.
 -Oh, let's go home.

713
00:40:14,455 --> 00:40:15,978
Tomorrow is another day.

714
00:40:16,109 --> 00:40:17,458
I thought
 everything went very well.

715
00:40:17,589 --> 00:40:19,025
LIAM: This has been a blast.
 MOLLY: Yeah, it has.

716
00:40:22,985 --> 00:40:24,204
LIAM: Look at this!

717
00:40:24,334 --> 00:40:25,248
TIFFANY: Anthony!

718
00:40:25,379 --> 00:40:26,859
-Uh-oh.
-MAN: Anthony?

719
00:40:26,989 --> 00:40:28,730
ALL: Anthony!

720
00:40:28,861 --> 00:40:31,994
You day-glow maggot!
 I thought you were home sick.

721
00:40:33,169 --> 00:40:34,562
I got better?

722
00:40:34,693 --> 00:40:37,260
Oh, yeah, you got better.
 That's it. We're through.

723
00:40:37,391 --> 00:40:38,697
-Oh, yeah?
 -I wouldn't date you

724
00:40:38,827 --> 00:40:40,394
if you were the last freak
 on earth, you worm!

725
00:40:40,525 --> 00:40:42,265
What do I care if you date me?

726
00:40:42,396 --> 00:40:44,703
Okay, okay.
 We can work this out.

727
00:40:44,833 --> 00:40:47,270
No, no. I'm sorry, Miss Lane.
 I just can't work with him.

728
00:40:47,401 --> 00:40:50,491
You can't work with me?
I can't work with you.

729
00:40:50,622 --> 00:40:53,276
No, you can't quit.
 The play is tomorrow.

730
00:40:53,842 --> 00:40:55,278
I'm sorry.

731
00:40:55,409 --> 00:40:57,542
It would be just too painful
 to do the play now.

732
00:40:57,672 --> 00:40:59,587
Even with
 a different Romeo.

733
00:40:59,718 --> 00:41:00,719
You maggot!

734
00:41:01,763 --> 00:41:03,243
I didn't know
 you had a girlfriend.

735
00:41:03,373 --> 00:41:05,985
-No, she ain't my...
 -Get lost, Maggot.

736
00:41:09,641 --> 00:41:13,253
Anthony, you're still
 gonna be in the play, right?

737
00:41:13,383 --> 00:41:14,602
No.

738
00:41:14,733 --> 00:41:17,126
If Tiffany won't do it,
I won't do it.

739
00:41:17,257 --> 00:41:19,912
Hey, I can feel just
 as much pain as she can.

740
00:41:26,135 --> 00:41:27,180
Thank you, Aunt Sue Ellen.

741
00:41:27,310 --> 00:41:29,487
Your welcome, Hillary darling.

742
00:41:29,617 --> 00:41:31,401
You put that
 in your college fund.

743
00:41:36,015 --> 00:41:38,583
Isn't there anybody else?

744
00:41:38,713 --> 00:41:42,848
Who can learn the whole play
 in 24 hours and act?

745
00:41:42,978 --> 00:41:45,372
Well, one out of two
 wouldn't be bad.

746
00:41:45,503 --> 00:41:47,026
PATTY: Ah, it's hopeless.

747
00:41:48,288 --> 00:41:49,942
We have to cancel the play.

748
00:41:51,813 --> 00:41:55,513
Uh, but couldn't you play
 the part of Juliet, Miss Lane?

749
00:41:56,252 --> 00:41:58,167
[CHUCKLING]

750
00:41:59,952 --> 00:42:01,519
Great idea!

